{"title": "Face on a Milk Carton", "content": "In the United States, starting during the mid-1980s and continuing until about the turn of the millennium, there was a practice of putting the faces of children who had gone missing (and were presumably kidnapped or abducted) on a milk carton, in an attempt to get neighbors of the person who had abducted the child to notice and report him or her.\n\nA Discredited Trope, if not a Dead Horse Trope. At this point, it has been parodied countless times and has entered the collective subconscious to the point that while people may not have actually seen an actual one in their lifetime, they still recognize it. In comedy, adults can make an appearance on the carton.\n\nThe United States has since developed the Amber Alert system, so within a few hours of an abduction a report of a missing child can be broadcast on TV or radio, sent via text message or in some cases posted on Expressway notice signs. This means that in some cases the announcement can be passed on to the public in mere minutes, which makes the several weeks notice it would take to get a photograph on a milk carton superfluous. They are supplemented by ADVO cards, which have an ad on the front and a picture of a missing child on the back, and are mailed regularly to homes. Many large stores also have a collection of \"missing\" posters displayed near the doors, where customers entering and exiting can see them, and some trucks and vans will have them on their back windows. In the Internet age, in addition to the Amber alerts, the family of the missing child may post something on the Internet. This can backfire, however: even if the child is found and the alert post is no longer relevant, it will still be circulated through email inboxes, blogs, and social media. And sometimes, well-meaning people pass them on, even if it turns out that they are misunderstandings, missing information, outdated, or outright hoaxes.\n\nMay also be used to Lampshade a character's disappearance or have part in a Mythology Gag, but is hardly ever played straight anymore unless it's a Period Piece.\n\nFor the book titled The Face on the Milk Carton, click here.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FaceOnAMilkCarton", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Janie", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/SilentHill1", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Roundhouse", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Janie", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/LoveAndRockets", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/AllStarBatmanAndRobinTheBoyWonder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Nightwing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Transmetropolitan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/AstroCity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/FunWithMilkAndCheese", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/SinCity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TomAndJerryTheMovie", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HoneyIShrunkTheKids", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/SinCity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheLostBoys", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Big", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HanselAndGretelWitchHunters", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Blackbird", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/SidewalkStories", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Janie", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/MercedesLackey", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheLovelyBones", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/DaveBarrySleptHere", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/MegCabot", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/OneEightHundredWhereRYou", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MarriedWithChildren", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MysteryScienceTheater3000", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/PodPeople", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ComedyCentral", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/EerieIndiana", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/SmallWonder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Lost", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheDailyShow", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/PunkyBrewster", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/VeronicaMars", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TrueBlood", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/PowerRangersTurbo", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MyNameIsEarl", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Supernatural", "/p